.SH "NAME"
constant::boolean \- Define TRUE and FALSE constants.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&  use constant::boolean;
\&
\&  use File::Spec;
\&
\&  sub is_package_exist {
\&    my ($package) = @_;
\&    return FALSE unless defined $package;
\&    foreach my $inc (@INC) {
\&        my $filename = File::Spec\->catfile(
\&            split( /\e//, $inc ), split( /\e::/, $package )
\&        ) . \*(Aq.pm\*(Aq;
\&        return TRUE if \-f $filename;
\&    };
\&    return FALSE;
\&  };
\&
\&  no constant::boolean;
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Defines \f(CW\*(C`TRUE\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`FALSE\*(C'\fR constants in caller's namespace.  You could use
simple values like empty string or zero for false, or any non-empty and
non-zero string value as true, but the \f(CW\*(C`TRUE\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`FALSE\*(C'\fR constants are more
descriptive.
.PP
It is virtually the same as:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&  # double "not" operator is used for converting scalar to boolean value
\&  use constant TRUE => !! 1;
\&  use constant FALSE => !! \*(Aq\*(Aq;
.Ve
.PP
The constants exported by \f(CW\*(C`constant::boolean\*(C'\fR are not reported by
Test::Pod::Coverage, so it is more convenient to use this module than to
define \f(CW\*(C`TRUE\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`FALSE\*(C'\fR constants by yourself.
.PP
The constants can be removed from class \s-1API\s0 with \f(CW\*(C`no constant::boolean\*(C'\fR
pragma or some universal tool like namespace::clean.
